05590nam a22008415i 9780857457905DE-B159720221107062033.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||221107t20122012nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808574579057 a10.1515/97808574579052doi  a(DE-B1597)635928  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aGN316b.S63 2014 7aSOC0020102bisacsh04a300223  aLB 390002rvk0(DE-625)rvk/90548:77200aSociality :bNew Directions /ced. by Nicholas J. Long, Henrietta L. Moore. 1aNew York; aOxford : bBerghahn Books, c[2012] 4c©2012  a1 online resource (228 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aWYSE Series in Social Anthropology ;v100tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tList of Figures -- tAcknowledgements -- tIntroduction: Sociality’s New Directions -- t1 Avatars and Robots: The Imaginary Present and the Socialities of the Inorganic -- t2 Imagining the World that Warrants Our Imagination: The Revelation of Ontogeny -- t3 Sociality and Its Dangers: Witchcraft, Intimacy and Trust -- t4 Group Belonging in Trade Unions: Idioms of Sociality in Bolivia and Argentina -- t5 Utopian Sociality. Online -- t6 A Sociality of, and Beyond, ‘My-home’ in Post-corporate Japan -- t7 Actants Amassing (AA) -- t8 Doing, Being and Becoming The Sociality of Children with Autism in Activities with Therapy Dogs and Other People -- t9 Materials and Sociality -- t10 The Art of Slow Sociality: Movement, Aesthetics and Shared Understanding -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe notion of 'sociality' is now widely used within the social sciences and humanities. However, what is meant by the term varies radically, and the contributors here, through compelling and wide ranging essays, identify the strengths and weaknesses of current definitions and their deployment in the social sciences. By developing their own rigorous and innovative theory of human sociality, they re-set the framework of the debate and open up new possibilities for conceptualizing other forms of sociality, such as that of animals or materials. Cases from Asia, Africa, the Americas and Europe explore the new directions of human sociality, illuminating how and why it is transformed when human beings engage with such major issues as economic downturn, climate change, new regimes of occupational and psychological therapy, technological innovations in robotics and the creation of new online, 'virtual' environments. This book is an invaluable resource, not only for research and teaching, but for anyone interested in the question of what makes us social.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 07. Nov 2022) 0aCollective behaviorvCross-cultural studies. 0aEthnology. 0aSocial actionvCross-cultural studies. 0aSocial groupsvCross-cultural studies. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh1 aAllison, Anne, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChau, Adam Yuet, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGeschiere, Peter, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKüchler, Susanne, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLazar, Sian, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLong, Nicholas J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLong, Nicholas J., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aMoore, Henrietta L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMoore, Henrietta L., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aSolomon, Olga, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aToren, Christina, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/rel